      <p>Sweet vs hot vs smoked, Spanish vs Hungarian, uses, and storage.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Comprehensive Guide</h2>
      <p>Smoked paprika (Pimentón) is made from peppers that are smoked and dried over oak fires. This gives it a deep, smoky flavor distinct from regular sweet paprika.</p>
    <h3>Sweet vs Hot vs Smoked</h3>
    <p>Regular paprika is typically sweet and mild, used largely for color. Smoked paprika comes in three varieties in Spain: dulce (sweet/mild), agridulce (bittersweet/medium), and picante (hot).</p>
    <h3>Spanish vs Hungarian</h3>
    <p>Spanish paprika is almost always smoked. Hungarian paprika is generally unsmoked, sun-dried, and prized for its vibrant red color and pure pepper flavor. Hungarian paprika comes in eight grades ranging from mild and sweet to quite spicy.</p>
    <h3>Uses and Storage</h3>
    <p>Smoked paprika is perfect for adding a barbecue-like smokiness to vegetarian dishes, stews, meats, and paella. Because its essential oils degrade in light, it must be stored in an opaque tin or a dark cupboard.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <h3>Is smoked paprika spicy?</h3><p>Not necessarily. The standard smoked paprika (dulce) is mild. You must specifically look for 'picante' if you want heat.</p><h3>Can I substitute regular paprika for smoked paprika?</h3><p>You can, but you'll lose the signature smokiness. Adding a drop of liquid smoke or using chipotle powder instead can help mimic it.</p><h3>How should I store smoked paprika?</h3><p>Store it in an airtight tin or dark glass jar in a cool, dark place to protect its color and flavor from light degradation.</p>
    </div>

